  "prompt": "How do I calculate mass of the moon using mass of the earth?",
  "response": "To calculate the mass of the Moon using the mass of the Earth, you need to know the ratio of the Moon's mass to the Earth's mass. The mass of the Moon is approximately 1/81.3005 of the Earth's mass. Here\u2019s how you can do the calculation step-by-step:\n\n1. **Find the mass of the Earth:**\n   The mass of the Earth (\\(M_E\\)) is approximately \\(5.97 \\times 10^{24}\\) kilograms.\n\n2. **Use the mass ratio:**\n   The mass ratio of the Moon to the Earth (\\( \\frac{M_M}{M_E} \\)) is approximately \\(\\frac{1}{81.3005}\\).\n\n3. **Calculate the mass of the Moon:**\n   You can find the mass of the Moon (\\(M_M\\)) by multiplying the mass of the Earth by the mass ratio:\n   \\[\n   M_M = M_E \\times \\frac{1}{81.3005}\n   \\]\n\n   Plugging in the numbers:\n   \\[\n   M_M = 5.97 \\times 10^{24} \\text{ kg} \\times \\frac{1}{81.3005} \\approx 7.34 \\times 10^{22} \\text{ kg}\n   \\]\n\nSo, the mass of the Moon is approximately \\(7.34 \\times 10^{22}\\) kilograms.",
